    rationale: "Wheals (urticarial lesions) are raised, erythematous, evanescent plaques caused by transient dermal edema. The mechanism is IgE-mediated mast cell degranulation releasing histamine, which increases postcapillary venule permeability, causing rapid fluid extravasation into the dermis. Wheals are characteristically transient (resolving within 24 hours) and migratory. Vesicles involve intraepidermal or subepidermal fluid accumulation, not dermal edema. Papules represent solid cellular infiltrates. Nodules represent deeper, larger solid lesions. Recognizing wheals as the hallmark of urticaria is critical for identifying allergic reactions in the perioperative setting.",
