    rationale: "The malar (butterfly) rash sparing the nasolabial folds is a classic finding of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). SLE is a multisystem autoimmune disease with anesthesia implications including: renal involvement (lupus nephritis \u2014 affects drug clearance), cardiac involvement (pericarditis, Libman-Sacks endocarditis \u2014 affects hemodynamic management), pulmonary involvement (pleuritis, pulmonary hypertension), and hematologic involvement (thrombocytopenia, antiphospholipid syndrome \u2014 affects coagulation and regional anesthesia decisions). Rosacea involves the malar region but includes nasolabial folds and telangiectasias. Dermatomyositis causes a heliotrope rash around the eyes, not a malar distribution.",
    metadata: { topic: "lesion-distribution", priority: "high" },
